\end{table}

Table \ref{tab:StandEffects} presents the expected standardized effects 
$\mathbb{E}(z_{i1})$ for combinations of true treatment effects $\theta_{i1} \in \{0, 0.4, 0.8\}$ and between-study heterogeneity values $\tau^2_1 \in \{0, 0.02, 0.06, 0.36\}$ assuming equal study sizes of $n_i=50$. As shown, larger true effects yield higher standardized effects, whereas increasing between-study heterogeneity reduces the expected standardized effects due to greater variability in the underlying study effects.

It is important to note that while our simulation uses a known missing data mechanism, \ie, selective reporting based on a logistic function of the one-sided $p$-value, no information about the cause of missingness is assumed to be available once the data are generated. This reflects the practical setting in which some outcomes are unreported, but their classification into, \eg, high risk or low risk of bias as per the ORBIT methodology is unknown. As a result, Copas et al. \cite{copas2019model} method, which requires the ORBIT classification and adjusts only for outcomes deemed at HR of bias, is not directly comparable to our methodology.

\subsubsection{Different factors for the simulation of ORB}
ORB is simulated under different simulation scenarios. We will consider the following values for selectively excluding treatment effects from the meta-analysis:

\begin{itemize}
    \item selection weight for outcome 1 $\delta_{1, \text{sim}}$ = 0 - 1.3, where $\delta_{1, \text{sim}} = 0.5$ corresponds to a moderate selection,
     \item the proportion of unreported studies for outcome 1: $1-p_1: 0\%, 20\%, 40\%$.
\end{itemize}

The selection weight will be explored over the range of values recommended by Carpenter et al. \cite{carpenter2011assessing}. The chosen proportions of unreported studies represent scenarios with no, low, and moderate degrees of missingness, allowing us to examine how increasing levels of ORB affect model performance.
We use a full factorial design leading to $14$ (selection weight) $\times 3$ (proportion of unreported studies) = $42$ scenarios.

\subsection{Summary of all considered simulation scenarios}

Table \ref{tab:SimStudy} summarizes the key factors and parameter values investigated in the simulation study. The design systematically varies characteristics of the meta-analysis (\eg number of studies, between-study heterogeneity, and correlations) and parameters governing the missingness mechanism. Crossing these factors allows us to evaluate the performance of the ORB-adjustment method across a broad range of meta-analytic scenarios.

To assess model misspecification, we vary 
$\delta_{1,\text{sim}}$ and $\delta_{1,\text{est}}$ independently. This design distinguishes between scenarios where the selection model used for estimation matches the true data-generating mechanism    ($\delta_{1,\text{sim}}$ = $\delta_{1,\text{est}}$) and those where it differs ($\delta_{1,\text{sim}}$ $\neq$ $\delta_{1,\text{est}}$). Thereby, MAR (and MCAR) scenarios are included to evaluate the robustness of the ORB-adjustment method under alternative missingness mechanisms.

Each simulation scenario is replicated $n_{\text{sim}}= 1900$ times to evaluate performance with adequate Monte Carlo precision. Within each replicate, the ORB-adjusted estimator uses $M=1000$ imputations to impute the unreported outcomes. Thus, $n_{sim}$ governs the number of repeated meta-analyses per scenario, while 
$M$ controls the number of imputations within each analysis.

Step 1, the simulation of the bivariate meta-analysis, involves $972$ scenarios and step 2, the simulation of ORB, leads to $42$ scenarios, which in total leads to $40824$ scenarios for the simulation study ($\delta_{1,\text{est}}$ is not included in the scenarios). 

