\section{Estimands}

Our primary estimand is the treatment effect size, derived from evidence pooled across multiple studies in the meta-analysis. This estimation is conducted using restricted maximum likelihood (REML), which maximizes a restricted likelihood function with respect to the variance components and then estimates the treatment effects conditionally \cite{mavridis2013practical}. We perform naive estimation, based on treatment effects solely from reported studies, complete data estimation, based on all studies before ORB is simulated, and estimation using our ORB-adjustment method. The statistical target of this simulation study is focused on estimation. Therefore, we aim to compare those three different estimation methods in terms of bias, MSE, and coverage probability (CP).

\section{Methods}
For a given parameter of interest $\theta$, we use REML to obtain its estimate using the \texttt{rma.mv()} function from the \texttt{metafor} package in R. REML estimation extends naturally to multivariate meta-analysis, where it jointly estimates the overall outcome-specific treatment effects $(\theta_1, \theta_2)$ and the between-study variance–covariance matrix. Each study contributes a bivariate effect vector $
(\hat\nu_{i1}, \hat\nu_{i2})$ and a corresponding within-study covariance matrix 
$\Sigma_i^{\text{within}}$.
The within-study covariance matrix can be incorporated via the \texttt{V} argument of the \texttt{rma.mv()} function \cite{viechtbauer2010conducting}. REML estimation corrects for the downward bias in variance component estimates that occurs under standard maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) and is therefore preferred for random-effects meta-analysis \cite{mavridis2013practical}.
Depending on the information, we compare the complete data estimation to the ORB-adjusted estimation. In the simulation study, we consider continuous outcomes for simplicity, whereas the real-data application in our manuscript involves binary outcomes which are analyzed on the log odds ratio scale or log relative risk scale. Using continuous outcomes simplifys computation and interpretation of performance metrics such as bias, MSE, and coverage. Importantly, in the simulation study, the outcomes serve solely as statistical quantities for evaluating estimator behavior, so no clinical or substantive interpretation of the simulated outcomes is intended.

Regardless of outcome type, the core estimation framework remains the same: a bivariate random-effects meta-analysis model is used to obtain pooled estimates and between-study variance components. We compare three estimates: 
\begin{compactenum}[(i)]
  \item the naive estimate, \item the complete data estimate (as baseline),
  \item the ORB-adjusted estimate.
\end{compactenum}

\subsection{Naive Estimate}

The naive estimate is obtained by fitting the bivariate random-effects meta-analysis model to the subset of study outcomes that were reported. Specifically, only the observed (non-missing) outcomes are included in the analysis, and the model is fitted using REML to estimate the pooled treatment effects $\theta_j$ and between-study variances $\tau_j^2$ for $j=1,2$. 

In practice, this corresponds to applying standard meta-analytic methods to the available data, ignoring the missing outcomes. The analysis implicitly assumes that missingness is unrelated to the unobserved outcomes and that the set of reported studies is representative of all studies. Under ORB, however, these assumptions are violated, leading to potential bias in the pooled effect estimates and underestimation of between-study variability \cite{copas2019model}.


\subsection{Complete Data Estimate}
The  complete  data  estimate  uses  all  studies  in the  meta-analysis  before  ORB  is  simulated. This estimator serves as a baseline for the true treatment effect in each scenario if there was no bias. 


\subsection{ORB-adjusted Estimate}

The adjusted estimate $\hat\theta_{\text{Adj}}$ for the current $\delta_{1,\text{est}}$ is given as
\begin{equation} \label{eq:weightedAverage}
\hat\theta_{\Adj} = \sum^{M}_{m = 1} w^{(m)} \cdot \hat\theta^{(m)}_{\MA} 
\end{equation}
where $\hat\theta^{(m)}_{\MA}$ is the combined estimate for each imputation $m$, $m = 1, ..., M$, based on a meta-analysis model. The meta-analysis used to compute  $\hat\theta^{(m)}_{\MA}$ consists of the reported study outcomes and the imputed study outcomes. The weights $w^{(m)}$ determine the contribution of each imputed meta-analytic estimate to the final adjusted estimate and depend on the specified selection weight $\delta_{1,\text{est}}$ and the corresponding imputed summary statistics (see our manuscript for methodological details). $\delta_{1,\text{est}}$ is the selection weight for outcome 1 used in the estimation step to explore the sensitivity of the ORB-adjustment method to assess the sensitivity of nonrandom selection. Setting $\delta_{1,\text{est}} = 0$ corresponds to a special MAR (and MCAR) case, implying that selection has no influence on inference.\\ 


We perform this adjustment under both univariate and bivariate meta-analytic frameworks. In the univariate case, outcome 1 (the outcome where ORB was introduced) is analyzed by itself, ignoring cross-outcome correlations. In contrast, the bivariate ORB-adjusted model jointly analyzes both outcomes using the covariance structure specified in the within- and between-study matrices. This allows borrowing of strength from the fully reported outcome 2 to improve estimation of the selectively reported outcome 1. We want to compare these two adjusted estimators regarding the gain in precision and bias reduction attributable to modeling outcome correlation explicitly.

Further methodological details on the ORB-adjusted estimator and its implementation can be found in our manuscript, where we also illustrate its use on real clinical data with binary outcomes. 


\section{Performance Measures}

The primary focus of the simulation study is estimation. Following the recommendations by Morris et al. \cite{morris2019using}, we evaluate the performance of the methods using repeated simulations and report bias, MSE, and CPs to assess simulation precision.  We let $n_{\text{sim}}$ denote the number of simulation replications.


We derive the number of simulations needed based on the treatment effect and the required Monte Carlo standard error (MCSE), \eg 0.5\% \cite{inthout2014hartung, morris2019using}. Our primary performance measure is coverage of the 95\% confidence interval and so 
\begin{equation*}
    n_{\text{sim}} = \frac{\mathbb{E}(\text{Coverage}) \cdot (1-\mathbb{E}(\text{Coverage}))}{(\text{Required } \text{MCSE})^2} 
     = \frac{0.95 \cdot 0.5}{0.005^2} = 1900.
\end{equation*}

The CP of the nominal 95\% confidence interval is defined as

\begin{equation*}
  \text{CP} = \frac{1}{n_{\text{sim}}} \sum_{r=1}^{n_{\text{sim}}} 
  \mathbf{1}\!\left( \theta_{\text{low}}^{(r)} \leq \theta \leq \theta_{\text{up}}^{(r)} \right)
\end{equation*}

with MCSE is calculated as
\begin{equation*}
    \text{MCSE}(\text{CP}) = \sqrt{\frac{\text{CP} \left( 1 - \text{CP} \right)}{n_{\text{sim}}}}.
\end{equation*} 


Our secondary performance measures are:

\begin{equation*}
  \text{Bias} = \frac{1}{n_{\text{sim}}} \sum_{r=1}^{n_{\text{sim}}} \left(\hat{\theta}_{\text{Adj}}^{(r)} - \theta \right),
\end{equation*}

\begin{equation*}
  \text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n_{\text{sim}}} \sum_{r=1}^{R_{\text{sim}}} \left(\hat{\theta}_{\text{Adj}}^{(r)} - \theta \right)^2.
\end{equation*}


MCSEs are computed for each performance measure to assess simulation uncertainty. 


\section{Limitations and Sensitivity Analyses}

As with any simulation study, several design choices may influence the generalizability of our findings. First, the data-generating mechanism assumes a logistic selection model for the MNAR mechanism, which is also used in the analysis model. This alignment may favor the ORB-adjustment method. To address this, we additionally include MAR scenarios to evaluate robustness under model misspecification. Because no observed covariates are included in the selection model, the MAR and MCAR scenarios coincide in our simulation setup. Alternative selection rules, such as two-sided selection, will not be explored here and may be considered in future work. For simplicity, we further assume that all trials have the same total sample size across studies. This homogeneity assumption reduces computational complexity and isolates the effects of between-study heterogeneity from variation due to differing study sizes. 

Second, although we employ a full factorial design, the simulation study is a simplification and explores only a subset of all possible parameter combinations. The chosen ranges for the selection weight, between-study heterogeneity, and between-study correlation are intended to capture representative and practically relevant scenarios rather than exhaustively covering the entire parameter space. This approach reflects typical meta-analytic settings reported in the literature while maintaining computational feasibility.

We assess the stability of our performance measures through $n_{\text{sim}} = 1900$ simulation replications per scenario, which ensures acceptable Monte Carlo error for bias, MSE, and coverage. MCSE for these quantities will be calculated and reported to evaluate the precision of the simulation results. 


\section{Other}

\subsection{Reproducibility}
We will upload the simulation protocol to OSF and GitHub. The \href{https://github.com/cburgwin/Outcome-reporting-bias}{GitHub} repository will contain both the R scripts of the simulations, and the files used to obtain the PDF of the reports, including this protocol. To guarantee reproducibility, the random seed of the simulation will be set to \texttt{seed = 20251210}.


\subsection{Statistical Software}

All computations will be performed using R version 4.5.0. The simulations will be run in parallel using the \texttt{parallel} and \texttt{doParallel} R packages. The \texttt{foreach()} function from the \texttt{foreach} package is used to loop over the grid which contains all simulation scenarios. Further packages needed for the data-generating mechanism are \texttt{MASS}, \texttt{Matrix}, \texttt{mvtnorm} and \texttt{MCMCpack}.

\subsection{Missingness}

The functions and R scripts of the simulations process make use of the \texttt{tryCatch()} functionality to stop the simulation in case of an error, and record the results up until that point. We expect no missingness in the data-generating mechanism. It has been shown that two studies are needed to do a meta-analysis \cite{valentine2010many}, however, fitting bivariate random-effects meta-analysis models requires a minimum number of studies to reliably estimate the between-study variance–covariance structure. The Cochrane DTA Handbook notes that fewer than four studies typically do not support such models \cite{macaskill2010cochrane}. The only simulation scenario where we could have less than four studies after the introduction of ORB is for the naive estimate for $k = 6$ and $1-p_1 = 40\%$, \ie when we have 40\% unreported studies for outcome 1 and 6 studies in the meta-analysis and base the estimation only on the reported studies. In those case we have less than four reported studies for the naive estimate, we report \textit{NA}.

To avoid running into convergence issues for the REML and resulting missingness in the statistical analysis, additional control parameters have been specified in the \texttt{rma()} and \texttt{rma.mv()} functions of the \texttt{metafor} package: the number of iterations has been increased to 1000 and the step length has been set to 0.1 for all simulation scenarios, \ie \texttt{control = list(stepadj = 0.1, maxiter = 1000)}. In some simulation replicates, model fitting may still fail due to convergence issues. We will repeat failed replicates until we obtain $n_{\text{sim}}$ successful replicates per scenario. This ensures that performance measures are computed on a fixed and comparable sample, reducing bias from arbitrary exclusions. We will also report whether missingness has occurred during the simulation study, following recommendations in the literature \cite{pawel2025handling, morris2019using}. 

\subsection{Computational Environment}
The simulations will be run on a Linux Server. A \texttt{sessionInfo()} output with more information on the
R environment and code to reproduce the simulation study will be made available in the \href{https://github.com/cburgwin/Outcome-reporting-bias}{GitHub} repository.
 

